Football, I imagine, in this tiny village is a mere yardstick of their humanity amidst the despair and famine. I certainly did not walk away feeling confident or at ease with anyone here, but the huge smiles, thumbs up, and pure excitement of seeing the whole group unabashedly cheering on a local children’s World Cup team with us elicited a complex collection of emotions for me: I felt proud of those boys – I felt grateful for the chance to be there with them – I was sad that they might never have the chance to leave this village with their blissful ignorance – I smiled and fist pumped because the technology of the world was finally helping the world – and finally, amidst the heat and the sweat, in the midst of this place I once loved so much and the decidedness that surrounded me, living here, I thought about my colleagues living in Porto, and I confirmed my newfound reality.

I was a far-flung advocate of Acumen.org – I was now a long distance marathoner.

For those who are unaware: Acumen is a global organization with 8 strategically-placed offices around the world – and I was on the Acumen Fund West Africa team based in Abidjan, Ivory Coast.
